Objective

This is a report file for using the dataset “California Housing Prices” from Kaggle. Below are some of the analysis and pre-processing that have been performed on the dataset. The below analysis lets us understand the importance of each features and the effect it has on the output. The dataset contains 20640 rows and 10 columns with the output variable as ‘median_house_value’ which determines the house price with respect to the features.

Reading the Data

Below is the code to import tidyverse and read csv (‘California Housing Prices’) from the system

library(tidyverse)
rhm <- read_csv('housing.csv')

The rhm tibble contains the following of 20640x10 values

head(rhm)

The Columns in the dataset are “longitude” “latitude” “housing_median_age” “total_rooms” “total_bedrooms” “population” “households” “median_income” “median_house_value” “ocean_proximity”

Pre processing of Data

The ocean_proximity column contains non-numeric values and hence we do index labeling by mapping all the unique values to numbers

output_var = 1:length(unique(rhm$ocean_proximity))
names(output_var) = unique(rhm$ocean_proximity)
output_var
##   NEAR BAY  <1H OCEAN     INLAND NEAR OCEAN     ISLAND 
##          1          2          3          4          5

Now that the values are mapped lets add it to the rhm tibble and remove the existing non-numeric column ocean_proximity

rhm$ocean_proximity_mapped = output_var[rhm$ocean_proximity]
rhm_numeric = subset(rhm, select= -c(ocean_proximity))

There are few NA values in the dataset and we remove it.

rhm_numeric <- na.omit(rhm_numeric)

After removing the NA values, the dataset is reduce to 20433x10 values (Only a few of the records are removed from the dataset and assuming it doesn’t affect the performance we continue)

Analysing the importance of features on the output variable

The correaltion of rhm_numeric tibble is as follows

require(corrplot)
corrOfRHM <- cor(rhm_numeric)
corrplot(corrOfRHM)

To check for the features that matter the most we could check for the absolute value of the features that are closer to 1.

rhm_df <- as.data.frame(corrOfRHM)
rownames(rhm_df)[which(abs(rhm_df$median_house_value)>0.1)]  
## [1] "latitude"               "housing_median_age"     "total_rooms"           
## [4] "median_income"          "median_house_value"     "ocean_proximity_mapped"
rhm_df <- as.data.frame(corrOfRHM)
rownames(rhm_df)[which(abs(rhm_df$median_house_value)>0.2)]  
## [1] "median_income"          "median_house_value"     "ocean_proximity_mapped"
rhm_df <- as.data.frame(corrOfRHM)
rownames(rhm_df)[which(abs(rhm_df$median_house_value)>0.3)]  
## [1] "median_income"      "median_house_value"
rhm_df <- as.data.frame(corrOfRHM)
rownames(rhm_df)[which(abs(rhm_df$median_house_value)>0.4)]

rhm_df <- as.data.frame(corrOfRHM)
rownames(rhm_df)[which(abs(rhm_df$median_house_value)>0.5)]  
## [1] "median_income"      "median_house_value"

By checking we could see that the variable mesian_income has very much effect on the output variable

Linear Regression

Lets analyze the outcome of of different models by fitting with different combinations of features from the above analyzed correlation

First, include the library MASS from CRAN to use the linear model.

require(MASS)

Fit the linear model for only the features with correlation value greater than 0.1 with the output

lm.fit = lm(median_house_value~housing_median_age+ocean_proximity_mapped+median_income,longitude, data = rhm_numeric )
summary(lm.fit)

Plots of features with output variable

A function that iterated with the features and plots the graph against the output variable.

colnames <- colnames(rhm_numeric)


for (colname in colnames){
  if( colname != "median_house_value"){
      plot<-ggplot(rhm_numeric,aes_string(colname,"median_house_value")) + geom_point()
      print(plot)
  }
}
